full_reasoning:
Step-by-step reasoning:

1. Key psychological mechanisms:  
 • Self‐interest – the monetary amount offered (split_self) is attractive in itself.  
 • Fairness reference – participants compare the offer to what they view as “fair”, computed from their token share (token_self) relative to the total tokens (token_self + token_opp) multiplied by the combined earning.  
 • Inequity aversion – deviations from fairness are penalized, but the penalty may be different when the offer is below fairness (“disadvantageous”) versus above fairness (“advantageous”). Participants typically are more sensitive to being short‐changed than to receiving more than the fairness benchmark.

2. How these mechanisms interact:  
 We combine self‐interest and fairness adjustment. The fairness reference, f, is computed as f = (token_self/(token_self+token_opp))×combined_earning. The deviation is measured on a logarithmic scale (i.e. D = ln(split_self/f)) so that multiplicative differences become additive. The absolute value of D is then multiplied by a “penalty” parameter that is chosen based on whether the deviation is negative (offer below fairness, controlled by lambda_neg) or positive (offer above fairness, controlled by lambda_pos).

3. Mathematical form capturing these interactions:  
 The model is piecewise such that:  
  • When the offer is lower than fairness, the penalty is lambda_neg × |ln(split_self/f)|.  
  • When the offer is equal or exceeds fairness, the penalty is lambda_pos × |ln(split_self/f)|.  
 This penalty is subtracted from the raw monetary offer (split_self) to yield the utility U_accept.

4. Parameters:  
 Two learnable parameters are introduced: lambda_neg (penalty weight when the offer is below the fairness reference) and lambda_pos (penalty weight when the offer is above the fairness reference). Their numerical bounds are chosen generously while being finite.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:  
 Observed behavior (the acceptance of an offer by the responder) is determined by the utility of accepting an offer. Each trial’s split_self, token_self, token_opp, and combined_earning provide the necessary input. The computed utility (which can be negative for an unappealing offer) is then used (by a later process with a temperature parameter) to predict choice probabilities.

